00:00:03.370 --> 00:00:06.930
&gt;&gt;commentatorDavid: We're fortunate to have
Jeff Ansell here today to talk, to talk about

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:09.360
his book, “When the Headline Iis You”.

00:00:09.360 --> 00:00:15.049
At Google we can, we can appreciate both sides
of-of news stories of the type that-that Jeff

00:00:15.049 --> 00:00:16.610
writes about.

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:21.730
One side you're worried that your-your words
are going to be twisted; you feel that-that

00:00:21.730 --> 00:00:27.899
the-the journalists are predators trying to-to
force things out of you that you don't believe,

00:00:27.899 --> 00:00:30.259
don't want to say.

00:00:30.259 --> 00:00:36.079
On the other side, we read articles that are
just bsB-S. We see interviews where the questions

00:00:36.079 --> 00:00:37.190
aren't being answered.

00:00:37.190 --> 00:00:43.660
Jeff from his background in journalism and
then advising people how to talk to-to journalists

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:50.800
helps us navigate the middle ground. How to
actually answer questions; how to not be a

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:56.850
stonewall and-and not be-be prey. And as a
result I think what he has to say is-is really

00:00:56.850 --> 00:00:57.850
relevant to those of us at Google.

00:00:57.850 --> 00:00:59.129
No further ado. Jeff , he's here to-to talk
to us about his book one that [unintelligible]

00:00:59.129 --> 00:01:03.230
you “When the Headline Is You” and I hope
you all have a chance to read it soon.

00:01:03.230 --> 00:01:05.220
&gt;&gt;Jeff Ansell: Thank you very much, David.

00:01:05.220 --> 00:01:06.220
Hey everybody.

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:07.220
&gt;&gt;female in audience: Hi.

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:08.220
&gt;&gt;Jeff Ansell: How's everyone today?

00:01:08.220 --> 00:01:09.220
&gt;&gt;some audience members: Good.

00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:10.220
&gt;&gt;Jeff Ansell: Good, good.

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:14.340
First of all I wanna thank you folks for the
invitation to be here; I'm very grateful.

00:01:14.340 --> 00:01:27.820
Thank you for having the interest to be here
as well.

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:30.220
[pause]

00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:36.140
I am a media and crisis communications advisor.
What I do is I help companies and governments

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:45.290
and individuals when they're caught smack
dab in the glare of the media spotlight; sometimes

00:01:45.290 --> 00:01:46.290
when the news isn't very good; and in fact
oftentimes controversial.

00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:50.750
I find myself working most often in cases
that can be considered tough, high profile,

00:01:50.750 --> 00:01:58.110
no win situations. I worked on the Erin Brockovich
case in California; I've trained White House

00:01:58.110 --> 00:02:02.820
spokespeople; I just finished a stint with
the Vancouver Olympics.

00:02:02.820 --> 00:02:09.899
I play a very modest role as a, as a faculty
member of the Public Disputes Program at Harvard

00:02:09.899 --> 00:02:10.899
Law School. I help instruct in the course,
‘Dealing With aAn Angry Public’ which

00:02:10.899 --> 00:02:11.899
starts tomorrow right next door, by the way.

00:02:11.899 --> 00:02:12.899
And I also have the opportunity to lecture
annually at Harvard Business School in the

00:02:12.899 --> 00:02:13.899
course ‘Negotiation Dynamics’. And what
I do is I work the MBA students to help them

00:02:13.899 --> 00:02:24.989
gain a degree of sensitivity to the impact
of values and emotion inand communication

00:02:24.989 --> 00:02:29.480
on the negotiation process.

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:32.670
So in the time that we have this morning,
I'm hoping that we can share some thoughts;

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:33.870
a couple of ideas about the state of journalism
today.

00:02:33.870 --> 00:02:43.900
Also I'd like to chat about why I wrote the
book and share with you some stories from

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:45.560
my days as a journalist.

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:50.819
And I invite you every step along the way,
please feel free to stop me, ask questions;

00:02:50.819 --> 00:02:54.080
I'll do my very best to answer as we go along.

00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:55.080
[pause]

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:57.130
If I may, I'd like to very briefly read just
a few paragraphs from the book that I think

00:02:57.130 --> 00:03:04.499
sets the tone for what this all about. It's
from the-the book's introduction.

00:03:04.499 --> 00:03:05.499
[pause]

00:03:05.499 --> 00:03:09.739
"Answering questions from reporters is risky
business. Though a media interview may feel

00:03:09.739 --> 00:03:10.739
like this great forward a straightforward
conversation, it actually represents a contrived

00:03:10.739 --> 00:03:11.739
and manipulative dynamic.

00:03:11.739 --> 00:03:14.329
Knowing how to talk to reporters is actually
like learning a new language, and it bears

00:03:14.329 --> 00:03:30.169
little if any resemblance to everyday conversation
and it's a mistake for anyone to believe otherwise.

00:03:30.169 --> 00:03:31.560
[pause]

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:37.730
It may seem as if speaking the truth should
be enough to build credibility and trust,

00:03:37.730 --> 00:03:42.779
but that's not the case. Exposing oneself
to media scrutiny requires more than simple

00:03:42.779 --> 00:03:49.200
candor. I; it requires knowledge, training,
and a keen understanding of how reporters

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:50.310
write the news."

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:52.680
Any in my nearly 40 years of experience doin'
this, I've yet to meet anyone for whom media

00:03:52.680 --> 00:03:54.650
skills come naturally.

00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:57.430
"Answering tough questions is difficult even
for reporters themselves.

00:03:57.430 --> 00:04:03.219
You'd think that being skilled in asking questions
would provide insight in how to answer them.

00:04:03.219 --> 00:04:08.450
I discovered otherwise, however, in a training
session that I conducted in Washington for

00:04:08.450 --> 00:04:10.209
famed Watergate journalist, Carl Bernstein.

00:04:10.209 --> 00:04:16.440
In the training, my first question to Carl
was about his troubled relationship with his

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:20.449
Watergate partner, Bob Woodward and to my
surprise Carl put his foot in his mouth so

00:04:20.449 --> 00:04:25.400
deeply it came out the other end, and I learned
something important that day.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:28.370
Anyone can ask questions, the real skill is
in answering them.

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:32.889
So it should be of little surprise then that
many executives and government leaders and

00:04:32.889 --> 00:04:36.680
spokespeople are reluctant to engage the news
media. Their concern is justified.

00:04:36.680 --> 00:04:41.160
People who talk to the media are only as good
as their worst quote. Though someone answering

00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:46.229
a reporter's question may strike all the right
notes for the majority of the interview, it

00:04:46.229 --> 00:04:49.020
takes only a single miscue to trigger disaster.

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:54.759
One misstatement to a reporter can destroy
long held goodwill or cause a company's share

00:04:54.759 --> 00:04:55.759
price to plummet.

00:04:55.759 --> 00:04:56.860
And I think legendary investor, Warren Buffett,
said it best: 'It takes 20 years to build

00:04:56.860 --> 00:05:00.650
a reputation; five minutes [laughs] to ruin
it.'"

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:07.490
Actually probably in this day and age less
than five minutes.

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:14.940
I was a pretty aggressive reporter. When I
used to show up for work every day, my editors

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:24.870
used to say to me, "Well Jeff, who's life
you gonna ruin today?"

00:05:24.870 --> 00:05:25.870
[laughter]

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:34.259
I was oftentimes about as popular as a, as
a, as a pig at a Bar Mitzvah.

00:05:34.259 --> 00:05:35.379
[pause]

00:05:35.379 --> 00:05:53.300
Now that I'm out of journalism, I-I've had
opportunity to think about why I got into

00:05:53.300 --> 00:06:13.449
it in the first place. And it's-it's funny
 -- I didn't see any of this when I was in

00:06:13.449 --> 00:06:31.909
it for 20 years, but I became a reporter I
think in part because I-I grew up angry.

00:06:31.909 --> 00:07:00.810
My late father was
a factory worker and I recall the callous

00:07:00.810 --> 00:07:20.760
way in which he was treated and it made me,
it made me upset that-that decent people were

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:31.930
treated in a very disrespectful fashion by
their employers. And it-it made me wanna fight

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:45.860
on behalf of

00:07:45.860 --> 00:07:52.180
the little guy, and being a reporter let me
do that.

00:07:52.180 --> 00:08:03.289
I didn't become a reporter right away though.
I left school at age 16. I sold encyclopedias

00:08:03.289 --> 00:08:10.159
door-to-door; I was a dishwasher; I was a
factory worker. I worked in a couple of different

00:08:10.159 --> 00:08:21.870
factories; I worked in a pantyhose factory
where I-I used to sew the legs in the pantyhose

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:35.250
together for three cents a dozen; I didn't
make very much money. And I worked in a clothing

00:08:35.250 --> 00:08:37.010
factory as well.

00:08:37.010 --> 00:08:51.130
My parents were-were very upset because I
was supposed to be a professional and how

00:08:51.130 --> 00:09:02.589
the heck did I end up doin' this?

00:09:02.589 --> 00:09:28.290
And-and one day when I was in the factory,
I-I called in sick because I was able to get

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:43.840
an audition for a local radio station. And
I was 16 years old but I told them I was 19;

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:52.959
I told 'em I was going to university even
though I hadn't even completed high school.

00:09:52.959 --> 00:10:10.399
And I did the audition and

00:10:10.399 --> 00:10:22.839
I thought I'd done a lousy job and went back
to the factory the next day. And then I got

00:10:22.839 --> 00:10:37.570
a phone call; not at the factory but to my
house telling me that I got the job.

00:10:37.570 --> 00:10:44.339
So though I-I terribly upset my parents, the
book is dedicated to my mother and father

00:10:44.339 --> 00:10:45.339
so things came together.

00:10:45.339 --> 00:10:56.770
And by the way, that-that pantyhose factory
was mistreating its employees. I did an investigation

00:10:56.770 --> 00:11:05.800
on them when I became a reporter so they got
what was comin' to 'em.

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:20.650
And the other ironic thing is the clothing
factory where I used to be a shipper and used

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:33.670
to schlep all these bundles on my back, they
later provided my wardrobe when I was a TV

00:11:33.670 --> 00:11:39.190
news anchor. So it's nice the way things turned
around.

00:11:39.190 --> 00:11:40.190
[pause]

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:46.310
When I was a reporter, I was very grateful
to do, to do a whole bunch of interesting

00:11:46.310 --> 00:11:50.060
things. There was one story that-that changed
everything for me.

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:51.060
[pause]

00:11:51.060 --> 00:11:57.310
It was about a young boy named Kevin. He was
about eight years old and Kevin didn't have

00:11:57.310 --> 00:12:06.360
a-a family; he was in foster care and he kept
getting shunted from one home to another and

00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:10.639
he was a very, very sad little boy.

00:12:10.639 --> 00:12:20.269
And I did a-a documentary on adoption and
I focused on Kevin. And to this day I often

00:12:20.269 --> 00:12:28.680
think that if-if Kevin found a home, it's
probably one of the most important things

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:33.610
I've ever done in my life; if he found a home
as a result of that story.

00:12:33.610 --> 00:12:44.220
And that's when I realized the power of the
pen and the camera. We can get an awful lot

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:45.220
done.

00:12:45.220 --> 00:12:56.290
As one of the stories I worked on, I posed
undercover as a drug addict for 12 months

00:12:56.290 --> 00:13:06.500
to expose doctors who were pushing drugs.
And I wired myself with a hidden microphone

00:13:06.500 --> 00:13:22.740
and I went to visit these docs every week
for a year; never once asking for drugs; never

00:13:22.740 --> 00:13:28.250
once did they examine me.

00:13:28.250 --> 00:13:40.009
And I can tell you that I collected an awful
lot of drugs from those guys. I put them all

00:13:40.009 --> 00:13:47.410
in a safe because the federal authorities
came to count the drugs after. And I'm grateful

00:13:47.410 --> 00:13:55.720
to say that both docs lost their licenses
and got what was comin' to them.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:14:09.810
I spent 12 months tracking Nazi war criminals
here in the United States and in Canada; found

00:14:09.810 --> 00:14:19.710
a couple of these guys. I got one shipped
back to Western Europe for trial; exposed

00:14:19.710 --> 00:14:21.010
the others.

00:14:21.010 --> 00:14:34.600
It was most distasteful to work on that story;
I hated every single minute of it.

00:14:34.600 --> 00:14:51.730
And when I was lookin' at the evidence that
showed how terrible these people were and

00:14:51.730 --> 00:15:07.639
how they destroyed innocent lives, I wanted
to put my-my-my hands around their necks and-and

00:15:07.639 --> 00:15:12.069
do the job myself. Thankfully we caught them.

00:15:12.069 --> 00:15:19.839
I spent a year investigating nursing homes
where I live. I planted spies inside homes

00:15:19.839 --> 00:15:28.040
'cause people weren't being treated right.
And I'm grateful to say we closed up one home

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:37.259
and we got some amendments to the nursing
home laws in the community where I live.

00:15:37.259 --> 00:15:38.259
[pause]

00:15:38.259 --> 00:15:46.170
I had a great run in journalism. And then
one day something happened.

00:15:46.170 --> 00:15:48.580
We were gonna go on the air for the six o'clock
news on TV, and we didn't really have a lead

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:51.579
story that day; all we had was a stabbing.

00:15:51.579 --> 00:16:01.650
And I never liked to lead the newscast with
a stabbing because as terrible as a stabbing

00:16:01.650 --> 00:16:07.320
is, in a major market station, you'd think
there'd be something a little more of significance

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.600
for everybody in the community.

00:16:09.600 --> 00:16:21.790
And it was about ten to six and as we were
getting ready to go on the air, the assignment

00:16:21.790 --> 00:16:28.040
editor got on the loud speaker and he announced
to the room, "Good news. We have a lead story.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:32.839
The stabbing victim died." [chuckles]

00:16:32.839 --> 00:16:42.889
And the newsroom erupted in a cheer. And that
was the day I left journalism.

00:16:42.889 --> 00:16:46.120
And it just was getting to me that was just,
that put me over the edge.

00:16:46.120 --> 00:16:50.690
So I thought, "Let me take everything I've
learned in the past 20 years and apply it

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:56.000
to another-another purpose." And that's why
I became what's called a media and crisis

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.250
communications coach; media trainer.

00:16:57.250 --> 00:17:04.830
I help people deal with the news media because
it sure ain't a natural playing field now.

00:17:04.830 --> 00:17:09.770
I know myself that when I was a reporter,
I’d say with great respect to the people

00:17:09.770 --> 00:17:16.030
I interviewed, "I can get anybody to say anything
I want." And I kinda feel bad about that now

00:17:16.030 --> 00:17:27.260
in some cases, but I was still in the process
of seeking redemption and this book is part

00:17:27.260 --> 00:17:29.230
of that.

00:17:29.230 --> 00:17:50.510
Because the process of answering questions
for media, as I said earlier from the introduction,

00:17:50.510 --> 00:18:06.820
is very unnatural. It can be like learning
a new conversation, a new language; it's stilted,

00:18:06.820 --> 00:18:13.480
it's scheming, it's manipulative, and can
be conniving.

00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:27.360
But I wanna be clear here, I didn't write
this book to bash the media. I'm very, very

00:18:27.360 --> 00:18:46.570
grateful for many of the things I had an opportunity
to do as a reporter. I shared some with 'ya’.

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:52.223
It's a noble calling and I'll always stay
in my head, it'll always stay in my head the

00:18:52.223 --> 00:19:02.140
quote by Thomas Jefferson who said, "I'd rather
have newspapers without government than government

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:04.170
without newspapers."

00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:12.640
Now there has been a revolutionary shift in
how news is produced and how news is consumed,

00:19:12.640 --> 00:19:19.610
and that's thanks in large part to you folks
at Google because the fact of the matter is

00:19:19.610 --> 00:19:30.490
today anyone can be a reporter. In fact, Matt
Rudge Drudge said, "We're all newsmen now."

00:19:30.490 --> 00:19:36.270
The problem is that we're in a state ofseeing
a continual dumbing down of the news these

00:19:36.270 --> 00:19:37.270
days.

00:19:37.270 --> 00:19:42.980
I mean just in the last week alone, what have
some of the stories been? Paris Perez Hilton

00:19:42.980 --> 00:19:49.340
will stop bullying people on his website,
that's in the news. Bristol Palin was [ ]kicked

00:19:49.340 --> 00:19:55.830
off “Dancing with the Stars”; that was
in the news. Keith Richards writes a book

00:19:55.830 --> 00:20:01.250
and describes Mick Jagger's private parts;
that's in the news, believe it or not.

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:02.614
And so this is something that's quite concerning.

00:20:02.614 --> 00:20:08.340
And there are a number of reasons for this
dumbing down phenomena. First of all, fewer

00:20:08.340 --> 00:20:09.870
consumers of news are lookin' for thoughtful
public policy discourse.

00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:12.880
We're told by so-called experts about diminished
attention spans the viewers, listeners, readers

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:14.130
have these days.

00:20:14.130 --> 00:20:19.010
Newsrooms themselves are experiencing a great
many cutbacks; people are losing their jobs;

00:20:19.010 --> 00:20:28.980
you have reporters who are doing more with
less. Now it's, you have some reporters who'll,

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:38.159
who will work for the paper and they gotta
schlep around a TV camera with 'em 'cause

00:20:38.159 --> 00:20:53.310
they gotta upload the-the information, the
and video to the Web; they gotta keep writing

00:20:53.310 --> 00:21:16.470
stories for the Web; and it's a, it's a, it's
lot of work on them now. And what it is, it's

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:28.891
research on the run and their they’re writing
history in a hurry.

00:21:28.891 --> 00:21:41.630
The problem is I think it's just it's just
too easy to become media road kill. It's too

00:21:41.630 --> 00:21:52.520
easy for decent, innocent people to say somethin'
that they wish they hadn't said. And there's

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:57.150
a lot of casualties along the way because
it's very easy, very easy to become negative

00:21:57.150 --> 00:22:00.740
and defensive and argumentative when you're
dealing with a reporter.

00:22:00.740 --> 00:22:05.320
And why? Because reporters approach stories
from a predetermined perspective; it's almost

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:12.350
a paint by numbers approach. And I didn't
realize any of this when I was journalist;

00:22:12.350 --> 00:22:16.660
I had to get the distance to figure this out.

00:22:16.660 --> 00:22:22.350
But if you look at any controversial story,
it's a predictable cast of characters.

00:22:22.350 --> 00:22:28.500
If you have controversy, the first character
you need is the victim. And I'm not trivializing,

00:22:28.500 --> 00:22:30.990
but somebody's gotta get hurt.

00:22:30.990 --> 00:22:37.470
If you have a victim, it means you need to
have a villain.

00:22:37.470 --> 00:22:50.140
If you have a villain and you have a victim,
it means you need to have a hero; somebody's

00:22:50.140 --> 00:22:53.169
who's ridin' in to save the day.

00:22:53.169 --> 00:23:04.179
Then you have a character that I call, "the
witness" who saw the whole darn thing happen.

00:23:04.179 --> 00:23:15.260
And then there's the character I call, "the
expert." And when I was a reporter I used

00:23:15.260 --> 00:23:26.730
to try to put the expert into a white lab
coat so they'd look official and be part of

00:23:26.730 --> 00:23:32.470
a narrative; they didn't even have to speak;
they'd look as if they were expert.

00:23:32.470 --> 00:23:36.860
And then there's the character that I call,
"the village idiot." And the village idiot

00:23:36.860 --> 00:23:42.570
is [chuckles] the one who really gums everything
up for everybody.

00:23:42.570 --> 00:23:50.530
And the risk oftentimes is that the villain
and the village idiot can be one in and the

00:23:50.530 --> 00:23:51.530
same.

00:23:51.530 --> 00:23:58.760
And I say respectfully if you look at the
recent BP debacle, the villain of course was

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:04.470
BP itself and the village idiot may in fact
have been the President Tony Hayward, who

00:24:04.470 --> 00:24:12.210
of course said a few things to the media that
I'm sure he regrets.

00:24:12.210 --> 00:24:13.210
But you know it's not even controversial stories
 ?

00:24:13.210 --> 00:24:14.210
[pause[

00:24:14.210 --> 00:24:19.240
that can pose risks. Even good news stories
are or stories [chuckles] that are supposed

00:24:19.240 --> 00:24:22.180
to be good news can be problematic.

00:24:22.180 --> 00:24:31.100
John Walter was named leader of AT&amp;T. They
held a news conference to announce it and

00:24:31.100 --> 00:24:39.070
then one of the reporters says to him, "Mr.
Walter, who was your service provider?"

00:24:39.070 --> 00:24:40.070
[pause]

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:49.240
And Walter didn't know how to answer, "I don't
know." And that day AT&amp;T's market cap plummeted

00:24:49.240 --> 00:24:50.240
four billion dollars.

00:24:50.240 --> 00:24:51.240
[pause]

00:24:51.240 --> 00:24:55.880
Now if you were advising John Walter, what's
the best answer for that question? What do

00:24:55.880 --> 00:24:56.960
ya think?

00:24:56.960 --> 00:24:58.040
&gt;&gt;audience: AT&amp;T.

