00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:38.520
&gt;&gt;male in audience: Right.

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:39.520
&gt;&gt;Jeff Ansell: Okay.

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:48.909
Anyway it was just a, that was the signal
of a very terrible time for John Walter and

00:26:48.909 --> 00:26:52.330
he didn't last terribly long at-at AT&amp;T.

00:26:52.330 --> 00:27:00.740
But most every company is one sentence away
from disaster. That's all it takes. Look at

00:27:00.740 --> 00:27:08.190
Tony Hay-Hayward, our friend from BP. Remember
his quote? What was his famous quote?

00:27:08.190 --> 00:27:12.059
&gt;&gt;female in audience: I want my life back.

00:27:12.059 --> 00:27:15.460
&gt;&gt;Jeff Ansell: I want my life back.

00:27:15.460 --> 00:27:26.250
Now here's the thing: it's quite conceivable
that Tony Hayward, when he made that comment,

00:27:26.250 --> 00:27:29.460
he made a number of other comments.

00:27:29.460 --> 00:27:35.460
Let's presume he delivered ten sentences and
nine of them were genuine and heartfelt and

00:27:35.460 --> 00:27:43.960
one sentence was, and he probably didn't even
mean it in a selfish way, but he says, "I

00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:46.940
want my life back."

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:54.570
Well you don't have to be a-a journalism professor
from Columbia University to figure out that's

00:27:54.570 --> 00:28:05.210
the one quote they're gonna use because you
are only as good as your worst quote. But,

00:28:05.210 --> 00:28:12.830
and the thing is people oftentimes, they'll
read the paper the next day, they'll watch

00:28:12.830 --> 00:28:21.190
TV, they'll see a quote like that getting
used and you know what they're gonna say,

00:28:21.190 --> 00:28:29.600
it's predictable. "Where's the rest of what
I said. They took me out of context."

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:38.179
No, no. T they weren't taken out of context;
they were edited.

00:28:38.179 --> 00:28:47.850
And that's one of the things I do is I share
with people strategies and techniques to make

00:28:47.850 --> 00:28:55.549
sure that every single sentence that comes
out of your mouth is honest -- number one,

00:28:55.549 --> 00:28:59.780
and that it works in your favor.

00:28:59.780 --> 00:29:04.860
But again it's too easy for reasonably intelligent
people to put their foot in their mouths.

00:29:04.860 --> 00:29:10.269
Sunrise Hospital, example, in New York, part
of the Columbia Hospital System.

00:29:10.269 --> 00:29:22.970
They had a terrible situation happen not long
ago when a homeless man showed up at the Emergency

00:29:22.970 --> 00:29:28.809
Room door and he went to the front desk and
he said, "Please I have terrible chest pains.

00:29:28.809 --> 00:29:31.070
C, can I see a doctor?"

00:29:31.070 --> 00:29:41.200
And the woman behind the counter said, "Well,
sir I need your insurance card." He said,

00:29:41.200 --> 00:30:06.380
"Ma'am I'm homeless. I know I smell, I know
I'm dirty, but I have a real bad chest pain.

00:30:06.380 --> 00:30:12.490
Can you please help me see a doctor?"

00:30:12.490 --> 00:30:16.730
"Sir, I need your insurance."

00:30:16.730 --> 00:30:30.340
Anyway what happened was they walked him out
the front door and about 30 feet from the

00:30:30.340 --> 00:30:37.240
front door, what do you think happens? He
keels over and he dies.

00:30:37.240 --> 00:30:45.340
He was a young man; he was in his 30's.

00:30:45.340 --> 00:30:55.899
So ABC News Primetime Live does an investigation.

00:30:55.899 --> 00:30:57.230
[pause]

00:30:57.230 --> 00:31:04.110
And Brian Ross is a very good reporter; he's
probably one of the best reporters around

00:31:04.110 --> 00:31:05.600
today; -- investigative reporters.

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:13.210
He's interviewing the PR person at Sunrise
Hospital and he says to her, "Well, what's

00:31:13.210 --> 00:31:24.409
your reaction to the fact that your Emergency
Room turned down this man because he didn't

00:31:24.409 --> 00:31:25.669
have insurance?"

00:31:25.669 --> 00:31:35.080
And she got all defensive and finally she
says, "Look it, we're all gonna die."

00:31:35.080 --> 00:31:36.080
[laughter]

00:31:36.080 --> 00:31:45.940
Now you know, if it you're Brian Ross and
you hear that quote, you know you just struck

00:31:45.940 --> 00:31:46.940
oil.

00:31:46.940 --> 00:31:53.899
But there's the papers are riddled on a regular
basis with people saying dumb things. Remember

00:31:53.899 --> 00:31:59.059
that earthquake in Italy about a year or so
ago?

00:31:59.059 --> 00:32:05.590
Sylvio Berlusconi, the Prime Minister Italy,
remember what he said to all the people who

00:32:05.590 --> 00:32:11.139
lost their homes? "Pretend you're on vacation.
Go to the beach. Go camping."

00:32:11.139 --> 00:32:12.139
[pause]

00:32:12.139 --> 00:32:18.130
You know and-and those are negative stories,
but a-a negative story doesn't even have to

00:32:18.130 --> 00:32:22.060
be true in order for it to get legs.

00:32:22.060 --> 00:32:28.070
More than a hundred years ago Mark Twain said,
"A lie can travel halfway around the world

00:32:28.070 --> 00:32:33.230
while the truth is still putting on its shoes."
And that was before television; before radio;

00:32:33.230 --> 00:32:35.360
before the Internet.

00:32:35.360 --> 00:32:38.300
So how much more true is that today?

00:32:38.300 --> 00:32:52.820
And I can tell ya that whether a person is
dealing with a negative situation that's real

00:32:52.820 --> 00:33:01.000
or not real, there's a particular response
pattern that people fall into. And you may

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:17.350
notice this on the news when you've seen you’re
seeing people who are being interviewed, oftentimes

00:33:17.350 --> 00:33:18.490
reluctantly.

00:33:18.490 --> 00:33:30.520
When somebody is confronted by a reporter,
the first thing they do is they stop breathing.

00:33:30.520 --> 00:33:40.690
The second thing they do is they stop listening.
The third thing they do is they feverishly

00:33:40.690 --> 00:33:48.110
say to themselves, "How am I gonna answer?
How am I gonna answer." ?" The fourth thing

00:33:48.110 --> 00:33:56.000
they do is they start arguing. And the fifth
thing they do is they have an out of body

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:57.000
experience.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:58.000
[laughter]

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:09.570
And of course when the story comes out, they’re
their very upset about it and what's their

00:34:09.570 --> 00:34:18.220
complaint gonna be, ? "Where's the rest of
what I said? They took me outta context."

00:34:18.220 --> 00:34:27.590
You see what a lot of people have to realize
is that when they're mired in bad news, all

00:34:27.590 --> 00:34:32.650
the facts in the world aren't gonna change
anybody's opinion,

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:33.650
[pause]

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:40.720
because bad news is driven by emotion. And
just about every bad news story that's out

00:34:40.720 --> 00:34:43.720
there has emotion attached to it.

00:34:43.720 --> 00:34:51.210
We deliver the ‘Dealing With an Angry Public’
course at MIT Harvard. And we get a bunch

00:34:51.210 --> 00:34:55.690
of people who take the course usually from
the ugliest sectors around. We get nuclear

00:34:55.690 --> 00:35:05.290
people and sometimes we get people from tobacco;
the gun lobby sometimes comes.

00:35:05.290 --> 00:35:15.650
And oftentimes somebody will stand up at the
beginning of a program, usually it's a, it's

00:35:15.650 --> 00:35:31.680
an engineer, with great respect. And the engineer
will say to everybody, "The reason we're taking

00:35:31.680 --> 00:35:38.790
the program ‘Dealing With an Angry Public’
is because we wanna help our angry publics

00:35:38.790 --> 00:35:46.020
learn how to strip away emotion so they focus
only on facts."

00:35:46.020 --> 00:35:51.450
And we get a good laugh out of that.

00:35:51.450 --> 00:36:04.860
Because if it's about a battle between fact
and emotion in the court of public opinion,

00:36:04.860 --> 00:36:10.960
emotion is always gonna win.

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:17.580
Now with a court of law or in the regulatory
world, facts will prevail.

00:36:17.580 --> 00:36:22.840
But most people fight their battles in the
court of public opinion.

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:31.460
And they-they often fight their cause by using
traditional public relations strategies and

00:36:31.460 --> 00:36:34.780
those strategies don't work anymore.

00:36:34.780 --> 00:36:37.750
Because one public relations strategy that
has been used and used and used is the one

00:36:37.750 --> 00:36:48.220
where the message is the mantra, . Oover and
over and over again the individual will repeat

00:36:48.220 --> 00:36:53.540
the same message regardless of the question
that's asked.

00:36:53.540 --> 00:36:59.200
And it just makes them look foolish because
each time they repeat the same question over

00:36:59.200 --> 00:37:13.390
and over again, it strips away a layer of
sincerity from them. And they think, "Well

00:37:13.390 --> 00:37:22.010
I'll show the reporter there's no way she's
gonna get me 'cause I'll just keep saying

00:37:22.010 --> 00:37:26.480
my message over and over again."

00:37:26.480 --> 00:37:42.540
But what I used to do when I was a reporter
is I would feature my question and the answer

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:54.320
and if I asked them five times and five times
they gave the same dumb response, I would

00:37:54.320 --> 00:38:07.130
feature that in my story. And so who's the,
who looks foolish now?

00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:08.130
[pause]

00:38:08.130 --> 00:38:15.330
The other mistake the traditional public relations
strategies make is to overwhelm people with

00:38:15.330 --> 00:38:23.020
data. "Well you know let me just share what
the numbers indicate here. You know if you

00:38:23.020 --> 00:38:25.701
look at the parts for per million they come
in;" it doesn't work. In part because the

00:38:25.701 --> 00:38:30.220
information that people deliver comes from
them and it's not credible when it comes from

00:38:30.220 --> 00:38:31.520
them. It has to come from a credible third
party source.

00:38:31.520 --> 00:38:33.600
The other thing is that very often people
in bad news are-are-are reluctant to refute

00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:34.930
the concerns of angry people. To, they, they
don't wanna engage angry people.

00:38:34.930 --> 00:38:36.790
So if people are suffering, very often a company
or organization will not want to acknowledge

00:38:36.790 --> 00:38:40.660
it. Why? Because it gives credence to their
perspective; it gives credence to their arguments.

00:38:40.660 --> 00:38:45.100
And so it makes people angrier when a company
refuses to acknowledge the harm it may have

00:38:45.100 --> 00:38:52.150
done or at least acknowledge the fact that
some people perceive there's been harm.

00:38:52.150 --> 00:38:59.440
Because when you're dealing with-with upset
people, there's two things they want. The

00:38:59.440 --> 00:39:08.580
second thing they want is-is, "Fix my problem."
The first thing they want is for you to acknowledge

00:39:08.580 --> 00:39:09.580
it.

00:39:09.580 --> 00:39:13.630
And what often stands in the way of course
are lawyers.

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:14.630
[pause]

00:39:14.630 --> 00:39:22.440
Lawyers have the ear of the CEO. And the lawyers'
expertise is in protecting the company in

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:32.610
a court of law and that's why the lawyer exercises
too much influence around the table.

00:39:32.610 --> 00:39:42.640
The problem, of course, is that a lawyer will
save you a hundred million dollars in a court

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:59.240
of law and cost you a billion dollars in the
court of public opinion in terms of lost sales

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:05.930
and so on. So who's the winner there?

00:40:05.930 --> 00:40:06.930
[pause]

00:40:06.930 --> 00:40:10.040
Also traditional public relation strategies
tell you that if you're a spokesperson, never

00:40:10.040 --> 00:40:13.240
use a negative word; never use, even-even
if it's a terrible situation.

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:18.740
I was training somebody who was a plant manager,
a whole bunch of plant managers, and we were

00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:20.840
simulating that day a-a-an accident at the
factory. And in the accident simulation, there

00:40:20.840 --> 00:40:21.840
were fatalities.

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:24.360
And so my question to the plant manager in
our simulation was, "What's your response

00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:27.260
to the deaths that took place in your factory
today."

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:32.260
And he says to me, "Well you know we're very
proud of our safety record."

00:40:32.260 --> 00:40:33.260
[laughter]

00:40:33.260 --> 00:40:39.290
"Excuse me? How can you say that given the
fact that there are people dead?"

00:40:39.290 --> 00:40:47.770
And what did he tell me? He had media training.
And the media trainer told him never say anything

00:40:47.770 --> 00:40:48.770
negative which is absolutely bologna baloney
and nonsense.

00:40:48.770 --> 00:40:51.110
Because sometimes you do have to do use negative
words,; otherwise people just aren't gonna

00:40:51.110 --> 00:40:57.610
believe you. If you're in a situation where
there's a high degree of concern and a low

00:40:57.610 --> 00:41:01.530
degree of trust, and it's difficult to carry
on your day-to-day business affairs, and you're

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:12.810
on the front page of the newspaper above the
fold, and they're talking about you either

00:41:12.810 --> 00:41:15.190
in Congress or the state legislature, then
it's time to use negative words.

00:41:15.190 --> 00:41:16.650
And a great example of that would be the JetBlue
debacle of a few years ago when the airline

00:41:16.650 --> 00:41:19.230
pretty well came to a standstill, stranded
many hundreds of thousands of customers. After

00:41:19.230 --> 00:41:20.250
David Neeleman who was the president at the
time came out and said, "I'm ashamed. I'm

00:41:20.250 --> 00:41:22.720
embarrassed. This never should have happened.
A lot of people were very, very inconvenienced

00:41:22.720 --> 00:41:23.720
and we apologize for that."

00:41:23.720 --> 00:41:24.720
But a lot of people are even afraid to apologize.
Again, why? Because it's the lawyer. If you

00:41:24.720 --> 00:41:25.720
apologize, it's gonna put us on the hook.

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:28.280
There was a story in Canada involving the
bad blood scare. Remember when the tainted

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:32.170
blood was out there? Red Cross around the
world was sourcing blood from San Francisco

00:41:32.170 --> 00:41:34.220
prisons if you can believe it. And a lot of
people got hepatitis and the AIDS virus.

00:41:34.220 --> 00:41:35.250
And in Canada, they held a Royal Commission
to investigate why this was happening. And

00:41:35.250 --> 00:41:36.600
the President of Red Cross was appearing before
the judge and the judge said to him, his name

00:41:36.600 --> 00:41:40.260
was Douglas Lindores, the President. The judge
said to him, "Mr. Lindores, do you now apologize

00:41:40.260 --> 00:41:41.940
to all those people who've been victimized
as a result of-of the inept actions of Red

00:41:41.940 --> 00:41:42.940
Cross?"

00:41:42.940 --> 00:41:43.940
And the President of Red Cross said, "Well,
Your Honor it's that easy, it's a."

00:41:43.940 --> 00:41:44.940
And the judge said, "Well Mr. Lkindores I
think it is very easy. Yes or no do you apologize?"

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:50.550
"Ah, well Your Honor I'm gonna have to consult."
"Sir, yes or no do you apologize?"

00:41:50.550 --> 00:41:51.910
And the headline the next day, "Red Cross
Refuses Apology."

00:41:51.910 --> 00:41:52.910
Now oOf course he's the former CEO of Red
Cross.

00:41:52.910 --> 00:41:53.910
But we should know that very often an apology
goes an awful long way towards mitigating

00:41:53.910 --> 00:41:57.430
damages in a bad news situation.

00:41:57.430 --> 00:42:05.580
I read about one company, The Covenant Transportation
Group here in the United States. Everyday

00:42:05.580 --> 00:42:06.580
its trucks travel one million miles here in
the United States alone. They've got 25,000

00:42:06.580 --> 00:42:07.840
trucks on the road and terrible things happen
now and again.

00:42:07.840 --> 00:42:10.170
And they have a policy, a new policy whenever
one of their trucks is involved in an accident

00:42:10.170 --> 00:42:12.790
or even a fatality, the president of the company
and the lawyer will call up the family and

00:42:12.790 --> 00:42:14.190
they'll say, "We’re sorry for what we caused.
We apologize. Is there anything we can do

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:15.190
to help you in the meantime?"

00:42:15.190 --> 00:42:16.190
And of course the lawyer for the family is
saying, "Get off the phone. They're trying

00:42:16.190 --> 00:42:17.190
to fool you. Get off the phone."

00:42:17.190 --> 00:42:18.190
And the company says, "Look -- do what you
have to do. Please sue us; do whatever you

00:42:18.190 --> 00:42:22.030
have to do. We understand that, but in the
meantime is there a mortgage payment, is there

00:42:22.030 --> 00:42:23.070
a tuition payment, is there something we can
do to help."

00:42:23.070 --> 00:42:26.390
And their insurance premiums have-have plummeted.
They're savin' an awful lot of dough.

00:42:26.390 --> 00:42:29.050
Same thing with the Michigan Health System.
They have a more forthcoming policy 'cause

00:42:29.050 --> 00:42:31.450
it used to be docs and then would circle the
wagon and we would refuse to acknowledge your

00:42:31.450 --> 00:42:32.450
problem. But now they-they've seen the merits
though of this way.

00:42:32.450 --> 00:42:33.450
And by the way, in-in 35 states across the
United States there is the Apology Act; four

00:42:33.450 --> 00:42:34.450
Canadian provinces have the Apology Act, as
well.

00:42:34.450 --> 00:42:39.630
What that allows a company to do is apologize
without it being used as an admission of liability

00:42:39.630 --> 00:42:40.990
in court. And it's-it's a very, very popular
piece of legislation that hopefully will spread.

00:42:40.990 --> 00:42:41.990
Because when bad news happens on-on your watch,
you have to be amongst those who's most aggravated,

00:42:41.990 --> 00:42:42.990
most upset, most discouraged, and most aggrieved.

00:42:42.990 --> 00:42:43.990
So my hope is that “Wwhen the Hheadline
Iis Yyou”, it will find several audiences.

00:42:43.990 --> 00:42:44.990
I hope it'll be of interest to folks who are
consumers of news, who are interested in how

00:42:44.990 --> 00:42:45.990
news is-is gathered, reported, interpreted.

00:42:45.990 --> 00:42:46.990
I'm hoping as well the book will be of interest
to public relations people, of and spokespeople.

00:42:46.990 --> 00:42:49.120
Journalists I hope will find interest in it
although it's many of the journalists, of

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:52.500
course, will-will look to these techniques
and will try to find them when their they’re

00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:53.500
interviewing people.

00:42:53.500 --> 00:42:57.750
But you know the-the whole book talks about
taking an honest, ethical, and forthcoming

00:42:57.750 --> 00:43:00.800
approach to-to dealing with the media so it-it-it
should be something that, well will in some

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:02.230
cases will stymie journalists, but they're
getting the truth nonetheless.

00:43:02.230 --> 00:43:03.230
And I'm hoping as well it will be of value
of to students of both public relations and

00:43:03.230 --> 00:43:04.230
journalism as well.

00:43:04.230 --> 00:43:05.230
And overall, I hope that what the book will
do is take those of us who are right now passive

00:43:05.230 --> 00:43:06.230
consumers of news; we watch TV, we're not
even thinkin'. We read the paper, we're not

00:43:06.230 --> 00:43:07.230
even thinkin'. I'm hopin' that this book will
turn people from passive consumers of news

00:43:07.230 --> 00:43:08.230
into sophisticated consumers of news.

00:43:08.230 --> 00:43:09.230
Folks, thank you so much for inviting me to
be here today. I'm very grateful.

00:43:09.230 --> 00:43:10.230
[applause]

